.TH \f3include-tidy\fP 1 "April 2, 2026" "PJL TOOLS"
.SH NAME
include-tidy \(em \f(CW#include\fP tidier
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B include-tidy
.BI "[-Xtidy " tidy-option ]...
.BI [ clang-option ]...
.I source-file
.br
.B include-tidy
.I other-option
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B include-tidy
is a command-line tool
that can be used to ``tidy'' the
\f(CW#include\fP directives
used in a C
or C++
file
by ensuring that it directly includes
header files from which it references symbols
and does not include header files
from which no symbols are referenced.
Either missing
or extraneous header files
are in ``violation.''
.SH OPTIONS
.B include-tidy
has three kinds of command-line options:
.nr step 1 1
.IP \n[step]. 3
.BR include-tidy -specific
options.
.IP \n+[step].
.BR clang (1)
options.
.IP \n+[step].
Other options.
.SS Include-Tidy-Specific Options
All
.BR include-tidy -specific
options are preceded by an
.B -Xtidy
option to distinguish them from
.BR clang (1)
options.
For exmaple,
in:
.cS
include-tidy -Xtidy --all-includes -I../lib source_file.c
.cE
the
.BR \-\-all-includes
option
is given only to
.B include-tidy
and the
.B -I../lib
option is given only to
.BR clang (1).
.PP
For the options below,
an option argument
.I f
means
.IR file ,
.I n
means
.IR "unsigned integer" ,
and
.I s
means
.IR string .
.TP 5
.BR \-\-align-column \f1=\fPn "\f1 | \fP" "" \-a " n"
Sets the column at which to align comments
after \f(CW#include\fP directives.
The default is 40.
.TP
.BR \-\-all-includes " | " \-A
Prints all include files,
not just those in violation.
.TP
.BR \-\-clang \f1=\fPf "\f1 | \fP" "" \-C " f"
Specifies the path to
.BR clang (1)
to use.
.TP
.BR \-\-comment-style \f1=\fPs "\f1 | \fP" "" \-s " s"
Specifies the comment style to use,
one of \f(CW//\fP,
\f(CW/*\fP,
or
\f(CWnone\fP.
The default is \f(CW//\fP.
.TP
.BR \-\-config \f1=\fPf "\f1 | \fP" "" \-c " f"
Specifies the path of the configuration file to use.
.TP
.BR \-\-line-length \f1=\fPn "\f1 | \fP" "" \-l " n"
Specifies the line length.
The default is 80.
.TP
.BR \-\-verbose \f1=\fPs "\f1 | \fP" "" \-V " s"
Specifies what to be verbose about.
Valid values for
.I s
are:
.RS 8
.TP 4
.PD 0
.B a
Command-line arguments.
.TP
.B i
Files included.
.TP
.B P
Configuration file proxies.
.TP
.B s
Symbols referenced.
.TP
.B S
Configuration file symbols.
.RE
.PD
.IP
Multiple values may be given,
one immediately after the other.
Alternatively,
\f(CW*\fP may be given to mean ``all''
or
\f(CW-\fP may be given to mean ``none.''
.SS Clang Options
Options that are neither one of
.B "Other Options"
nor preceded by
.B -Xtidy
are
.BR clang (1)
options
and are passed to
.B clang
(libclang)
verbatim.
.SS Other Options
These options are given directly as-is
since they would never be ambiguous
with
.BR clang (1)
options.
.TP 5
.BR \-\-help " | " \-h
Prints a help message
for command-line options
and exits.
.TP
.BR \-\-version " | " \-v
Prints the version number
and exits.
.SH CONFIGRATION FILES
A configuration file
can be used to configure
.B include-tidy
by reading it
on start-up.
.PP
The file's full path
is derived from the first of these files
that exists
and is readable:
.nr step 1 1
.IP \n[step]. 3
The value of either the
.B \-\-config
or
.B \-c
option.
.IP \n+[step].
.B ./include-tidy.toml
.IP \n+[step].
The first of these files:
.RS 8
.TP
.PD 0
.B $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/include-tidy.toml
.TP
.B ~/.config/include-tidy.toml
.RE
.PD
.IP \n+[step].
If the
.B XDG_CONFIG_DIRS
environment variable
is set to a colon separated list of paths,
then for each
.I path
in it,
the first of
.IB path /include-tidy.toml \f1.\fP
.IP \n+[step].
.B /etc/xdg/include-tidy.toml
.SH EXIT STATUS
.PD 0
.IP 0
Success.
.IP 64
Command-line usage error.
.IP 65
Source file has one or more errors.
.IP 66
Open file error.
.IP 69
Either could not invoke
.BR clang (1)
or get the current working directory.
.IP 70
Internal software error.
(Please report the bug.)
.IP 71
Operating system error.
.IP 74
I/O error.
.IP 78
Configuration file error.
.PD
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B HOME
Used to locate a default configuration file
under the user's home directory.
If unset,
the home directory is obtained from the password database entry
for the effective user.
If that fails,
no default configuration file
under the user's home directory
is read.
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_DIRS
If set to a colon separated list of paths,
then for each
.I path
in it,
the first of
.IB path /include-tidy
to exist
and be readable
is used as the configuration file
(see
.BR include-tidy (5)).
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
If set to a path
of a directory
and
.B $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/include-tidy
exists and is readable,
then that used as the configuration file
(see
.BR include-tidy (5)).
.SH FILES
.TP
.B $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/include-tidy
.PD 0
.TP
.B ~/.config/include-tidy
.TP
.B /etc/xdg/include-tidy
.PD
The default configuration file.
.SH AUTHOR
Paul J. Lucas
.RI < paul@lucasmail.org >
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR clang (1),
.BR sysexits (3),
.BR include-tidy (5)
